Yes—adjacent things exist, but your exact framing is distinct.

Existing neighbors:

* Metaballs / implicit surfaces use overlapping fields to create smooth “blobby” forms.  ￼
* Radial basis function deformation uses control points to smoothly deform meshes.  ￼
* Puppet / handle-based deformation lets high-level controls move triangle meshes. Adobe’s Puppet Tool still relies on triangle meshes underneath.  ￼
* Dual mesh / triangle-center methods already track relationships between triangle centers in some simulation contexts.  ￼

What seems different in your idea is the circle-halo relationship layer:

triangles render the body; circles track the field; vesicas encode relationships; animation expresses overlap.

I added it to Pantheon/Money Bin as:

Vesica Control Mesh / Circle-Halo Animation Layer

Core design:

Triangle mesh = visible/render layer
Circle halos  = invisible relationship/control layer
Vesicas       = overlap zones between neighboring halos
Output        = smoother deformation + meaning-aware animation

Key formula:

influence(i,j) =
overlap_area(circle_i, circle_j) / min(area_i, area_j)

Then each triangle updates from its own motion plus weighted neighbor influence:

motion_i =
own_motion_i + Σ overlap_weight(i,j) * neighbor_motion_j

Best claim:

Not a replacement for triangles.
A higher-order control grammar above triangles.

That’s the improvement: not raw rendering speed, but relationship-aware smoothing, symbolic motion, and organic deformation control.